next: import-cycle-diagnostic — busi-reported (busi p5 dispatch.ssc decomposition). A true module import cycle (A→B→A, e.g. a sub-module importing back from the facade that imports it) currently overflows the JVM stack with a bare StackOverflowError and NO module-resolution message — the cause (a cycle) is invisible. Distinct from the FIXED diamond/DAG re-eval (the moduleCache dedup). ROOT CAUSE: SectionRuntime.runImport's `interp.moduleCache.getOrElseUpdate(resolvedPath, { c.run(childModule) })` only inserts AFTER the body completes, so a cyclic re-entry never finds the in-progress module in the cache → recurses forever. FIX (design): add a shared, ordered in-progress set `moduleLoading: mutable.LinkedHashSet[os.Path]` threaded into child Interpreters exactly like `moduleCache` (Interpreter.scala ~line 119 constructor param). In runImport (SectionRuntime.scala ~line 315), BEFORE getOrElseUpdate: if `interp.moduleLoading.contains(resolvedPath)` then throw InterpretError naming the cycle (filenames of moduleLoading chain + resolvedPath, joined by ' → '). Wrap the load body: add resolvedPath to moduleLoading, `try { build+run child } finally moduleLoading -= resolvedPath`. Purely diagnostic — no semantic change for the acyclic/diamond cases that already work (InterpModuleDedupTest stays green). TEST: new multi-file real-harness test InterpImportCycleTest (mirror InterpModuleDedupTest pattern): (a) A↔B 2-cycle and (b) facade↔leaf cycle → assert InterpretError with 'cycle' in message, NOT StackOverflowError; plus a control acyclic re-export still works. Spec specs/import-cycle-diagnostic.md. sbt: cd <worktree> && sbt "backendInterpreter/testOnly *InterpImportCycleTest" + run InterpModuleDedupTest for no-regression. BUGS.md entry (busi-reported). After: report SHA to busi.
